            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@endolith: The use of &lt;code&gt;enum&lt;/code&gt;s for sets of related constants goes back a long way in c programing. I suspect that with modern compilers the only advantage over &lt;code&gt;const short&lt;/code&gt; or whatever is that they are explicitly grouped together. And when you want them for something &lt;i&gt;other&lt;/i&gt; than bitmasks you get the automatic numbering. In c++ of course, they also form distinct types which gives you a little extras static error checking.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;/users/2509/dmckee-ex-moderator-kitten&quot; title=&quot;95,126 reputation&quot; class=&quot;comment-user&quot;&gt;dmckee --- ex-moderator kitten&lt;/a&gt;
